I like what David Lynch said:
"Ideas are like fish.
If you want to catch little fish, you can stay in the shallow water. But if you want to catch the big fish, you've got to go deeper.
Down deep, the fish are more powerful and more pure. They're huge and abstract. And they're very beautiful."

Most people I see today do not think like this, but I want to.

Martin: a Manifesto

Basic level happiness / easy solveable:
- Human animal -> Buy stuff for myself / foosball tournament where I want to win.
- Human connection -> Sharing a bottle of wine with a friend.
- Nature/adventure -> Ski, kayak, mountainbike or hike.

Advanced level happiness / hard to solve:
- Being able to focus down on an important subject I choose and create something special. (Meditation, music, be good at what you do)
- Out of body experience when sharing a project with good friends and witnessing their reactions.

What stresses me out:
- Being told what to create and failing at it. (school, Ditmer)
- Being told the direct, but not true solution to something. ("Martin sets the table" vs. "Can you set the table Martin?")
- Not being able to keep my own train of thought. (easy way out)

What I think is happiness:
"Being able to work effectively towards something meaningful to me, find it and witness others embracing the result."


